VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON LA 1 2 LANE UNDIVIDED ROADWAY DOWN INCLINE.  PHYSICAL EVIDENCE AT THE SCENE INDICATED THAT VEHICLE LEFT ROADWAY TO RIGHT, IN GRADUAL SLOW DEPARTURE FROM PAVED PORTION OF ROADWAY.   ENTERED DRAINAGE DITCH, OVERTURNED.   DRIVER STATED TO INVESTIGATING OFFICER THAT CELL PHONE FELL AND HE REACHED TO RETRIEVE FROM FLOORBOARD THAT VEHICLE MOVED OFF SHOULDER OF ROAD AND HE WAS UNABLE TO RECOVER.  DRIVER AIR LIFTED TO AREA HOSPITAL FOR MULTIPLE NON-FATAL SERIOUS INJURIES.  APPROX 300 GAL. OF PRODUCT RELEASED FROM OVERTURNED TRAILER THROUGH VENT AND OVERFILL LINES.   IN-HOUSE PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO SCENE TO FACILITATE RECOVERY OF UNITS AND DEBRIS.  OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR EMPLOYED TO REMEDIATE SCENE TO SATISFACTION OF STATE AND LOCAL ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES.   DRIVER CITED FOR CARELESS HANDLING OF A HAZ/MAT.

column168: On November 12, 2005 at approximately 0825 hrs EST an Alvan Motor Freight tractor-trailer arrived at the terminal in Perrysburg, Ohio.  Upon exiting the tractor the driver noticed a strong paint odor coming from the trailer.  He opened the trailer doors and found a fifty five (55)gallon drum of UN1193 leaking from a puncture approximately three (3) inches from the bottom seal.  ERS of Ohio was dispatched for clean up.  ERS personnel overpacked the damaged drum, cleaned up all free liduids, and decontaiminated all impacted freight.

column168: Driver stopped at rest area and noticed small amount of unknown material leaking from trailer. Emergency response personnel were dispatched to scene. Trailer was opened to ventilate. After entry it was discovered that three totes of Compound/Cleaning Liquid had tipped in transit and released material into trailer. Load was removed, neutralized, secured and reloaded.Freight was returned to shipper with clean up materials. Disposition is pending with shipper.  Improper securing of load was determined to be possible cause of release.

column168: On 11-15-2005 a Philip employee contacted the undersigned and advised that we had a trailer in our yard that was leaking. The undersigned responded and found a blue/green liquid dripping from the bottom of the trailer to the ground below. A crew was called in and the trailer unloaded and a 55 gallon drum was discovered to be leadking through a small pin hole approximately 15 inches from the bootom of the drum.  The liqid was identified, placed in an overpack and put back into the load.  The soil under the trailer was dug up and placed in 3 triwall boxes(1 yd. each) and placed with the load for disposal.  A sample of soil from the existing hole was taken and an analytical done for contaminates, it came back clean save a minute trace of motor oil.

column168: RailCar#GATX3689 was being pressure off-loaded using nitrogen into tanker#2122 at Onyx's rail transfer facility located in Port Arthur, TX.  The tanker was approximately 90% loaded when the rupture disk on the tanker failed due to over-pressurization, causing liquid material to spill onto secondary containment. The operator immediately shut down the operation and spread absorbent over the spilled material. After absorbing liquid, the material was collected and placed into spill clean up drums (55 gallon poly drums).  The drums containing the spill clean up waste will be sent for disposal by incineration.
column169: Existing procedures will be reviewed to ensure that the designed pressure rating is clearly outlined in the procedure to prevent exceeding designed rating. Operators will be trained on the procedure to ensure that they understand what the designed ratings are and how to adjust the pressure regulator so the designed pressure rating will not be exceeded in the future.

column168: We had a NH3 release when the hose between the tank and the applicator ruptured. This was in the middle of a farm field where the NH3 was being applicated. 2 plastic bins approximately 4'x 4' in size were filled with plastic jerricans. The jerricans were stacked one on top of the other and appear to be made for stacking as each container has 4 small raised locations on the top that fits into the bottom of a jerrican stacked on top of it. One jerrican was found leaking from one of the 4 raised locations on the top. It appears that the bottom can rubbed against the can stacked on top of it during transit rubbing a small hole into the jerrican.     The terminal that found the spill actually smelled the material and contacted ABF Safety & Security. We contacted the shipper and got directions on handling the product. The single leaking container was separated from the other containers, the shipper sent another container for the damaged product to be placed in. The damaged product was sent back to the shipper.
column169: The container may have failed from either being a defective container or by the bouncing and vibration that occurs during transportation on a trailer. Some dunnage may need to be added between the jerricans to prevent this type of failure.

column168: DRIVER LOADED AT PLANT IN BEAUMONT.  DRIVER DID NOT CHECK INTERNAL OR EXTERNAL VALVE, BOTH VALVES WERE OPEN AND WHEN HE REMOVED DUST CAP OFF REAR DISCHARGE VALVE SULFURIC ACID WAS RELEASED DURING UNLOADING.  DRIVER CLOSED HYDRAULIC VALVE CLOSING INTERNAL VALVE STOPPING THE RELEASE OF SULFURIC ACID.  FIFTY GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WAS RELEASED FROM TRAILER AND WAS CLEANED UP BY AES PERSONNEL USING SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE AREA TO A PH OF 7, THEN AES WASHED AREA TO THEIR WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT.  DRIVER RECEIVED SMALL BURN ON WRIST AREA FROM SULFURIC ACID.
column169: RETRAIN DRIVER TO LOOK FOR VALVES OPEN BEFORE LOADING.  HAVE A CHECK LIST FOR DRIVER TO USE FOR PRE LOADING AND UNLOADING.

column168: FILE-05-365 DOT SHIPPER-FLINT INK AWB#-DAG 37963681840 RIC  ON 11/09/2005 AT 0059, AN ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPROTED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT BUILDING LOCATED AT ABXAIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. column168: Portable tank was observed to be leaking or "venting" from a line from a tank level sensor to a level gauge. Ice was beginning to form at the point of the suspected leak. Therefore, we investigating further by chipping away at the ice. It was then confirmed that the leak was indeed at this point. The tank was isolated and the customer was notified. By the time the customer arrived, the leaking pipe was frozen over completely by a large block of ice and the tank level had been reduced significantly. The customer has made arrangements to relocate this tank container to their own facilities for repairs.  END
column169: Recommended that the shipper provide increased inspections prior to shipping their tanks.

column168: Driver delivered part of the product to a customer.  He cracked the dome lid on the cargo tank to relieve the pressure after the unload and forgot to secure it before getting back on the road to go to the next customer.  He traveled approximately 3 miles from the customer and was stopped by another driver who told him he was leaking a light stream of product for about 1.5 miles.  Driver pulled over.  Local authorities arrived on the scene shortly thereafter.  The fire dept called in the city/county crew to sand the leakage.  We contracted Garner Environmental to clean up the spill.  They used a street sweeper and bobcat to clean up the sand and product. Outside of trailer was wiped down so it didn't drip, dome was secured and driver went to tankwash to get outside of trailer washed.  The state of Louisiana was notified of the incident within the hour of discovery.
column169: This was clearly driver error.  He has received remedial training on proper procedure.

column168: THE YARD-MASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BARR YARD IN RIVERDALE, IL REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, GATX 300846, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED XYLENES, WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 DROP PER 2 SEC.   CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER, ASHLAND, INC., WAS NOTIFIED VIA THEIR EMERGENCY CONTACT TELEPHONE NUMBER.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE ABOUT 1/4 TURN.  THEY TIGHTENED THE OPERATING ROD CLOSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED AND CLEANED.  THE CAP GASKET APPEARED TO BE OK.  THE CAP WAS THEN INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE DRIP WAS STOPPED.  APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  ASHLAND WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.
Driver failed to open by-pass valve causing the hose to rupture and spill product.  Third party was contracted to clean up spill.

column168: A BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM GATX 15844 THAT WAS STANDING IN A YARD TRACK APPROXIMATELY 15 CARS DEEP FROM THE END RAILCAR IN THE TRACK.  INITIAL INSPECTION FROM BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS REVEALED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE 75 PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV).  THE SRV WAS ENCLOSED WITHIN A PLASTIC BAG AND GATX 15844 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED AND ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WASHED AND CLEANED THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE THAT HAD ACCUMULATED AROUND THE BASE OF THE SRV.  THE BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS DEPRESSURIZED GATX 15844 AND INSPECTED THE SRV.  ALSO, THE PRODUCT OUTAGE INSIDE THE TANK CAR WAS MEASURED AT APPROXIMATELY ELEVEN INCHES.  THE MECHANICS OF THE SRV APPEARED NORMAL, BUT THE 0-RINGS ALONG WITH THE SRV MOUNTING FLANGE GASKET APPEARED TO HAVE SOME IRON SCALING ON THEM.  IT IS UNKNOWN IF THE SCALING ON THESE ITEMS WERE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THE LIQUID RELEASE FROM THE SRV.  THE O-RINGS WERE REPLACED IN KIND AND THE FLANGE GASKET WAS WIPED CLEAN.  THE SRV WAS REINSTALLED AND SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED BY 1400 HRS. CDT, 11/09/05.  NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR OR LIQUID RELEASE WAS EVIDENT AFTERWARDS.  LIQUID EXPEILLED FROM A PROPERLY BOLTED SRV USUALLY RESULTS FROM AN OVERLOAD CONDITION, AN EXCESSIVE COUPLING SPEED EVENT OF SRV MALFUNCTION.  THE SHIPPER WILL BE NOTIFIED TO BENCH TEST GATX 15844'S SRV.  THE SRV WAS LAST TESTED IN 1996 GATX EC AND DUE FOR RETEST IN 2006.

UNDER THE GAUGING ROD ROVER, THE RESPONDER FOUND THE PIPE NIPPLE PACKING GLAND NUT (PGN) FOR THE SLIP TUBE GAUGE ROD 4 TURNS LOOSE.  THE PGN WAS TOOL TIGHTENED WHICH ELIMINATED PRODUCT VAPOR FROM THIS ORIFICE.  RESPONDER ALSO FOUND THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN WITH THE SAMPLE LINE CLOSURE PLUG 1/2 TURN LOOSE.  RESPONDER CLOSED THE SAMPLE LINE AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE SAMPLE LINE PLUG.  AFTER THIS SECUREMENT, NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR WAS DETECTABLE.  THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS CLOSED AND A BNSF SEAL APPLIED.  ALL SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED BY 0020 HRS. PST, 11/07/05.

column168: A FRA INSPECTOR DISCOVERED AND REPORTED RTRX 3003 IN RAILYARD EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR.  THE BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER THAT INSPECTED RTRX 3003 FOUND THE PACKING GLAND NUT (PGN) ON THE OPEN GAUGING DEVICE LOOSE AND THE RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED THE PGN WHICH ELIMINATED THE PREPONDERANCE OF THE PRODUCT ODOR.  A MINOR VAPOR LEAK WAS STILL DETECTABLE FROM THE SAMPLE LINE AT THE THREADED CONNECTION OF THE PIPE NIPPE AND THE PRESSURE PLATE.  "PLUG AND DIKE" MATERIAL WAS APPLIED AROUND A SMALL CRACK AT THE PIPE NIPPLE'S THREADS.  AFTER THIS MATERIAL CURED, NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR OR LEAK WAS EVIDENT.  A FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL (FRA-05110281) WAS GRANTED TO MOVE RTRX 3003 TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING.  AFTERWARDS, A GATX MOBILE REPAIR UNIT MADE REPAIRS TO THE SAMPLE LINE.

Driver noticed “A” side liquid valve on rail car was not seating properly and leaking minutely when he finished unloading from the rail car.  Driver replaced the plug in the valve and notified the corporate office.  Another driver was dispatched to check on the valve and found that by moving the handle slightly, he could get the valve to properly seat, stopping the leak.  Car will be emptied, degassed and the valve replaced.  Less than 5 pounds of product was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

Driver noticed “B” side liquid valve packing on the rail car was leaking minutely when he finished unloading from the rail car.  Driver tried to tighten the packing and was unable to do so.  He then closed the valve and the leak stopped.  Driver depressurized unloading hoses and replaced the plug in the valve.  Driver then contacted corporate office.  The Fleet Manager was dispatched to evaluate the situation.  He was able to tighten the packing nut and the valve no longer leaked when it was opened.  Less than 5 pounds of product was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: Driver went off the edge of the asphalt, no shoulder available, over compensated, lost control of vehicle and vehicle overturned.  Damage to bobtail resulted in hose connection to meter vapor eliminator being broken off and product leaked out. Unfortunetely an off-duty fireman that assisted the driver out of the vehicle moved the driver away from the vehicle and would not allow the driver to go back and secure the valve that controlled the breached piping.  If the driver had been allowed to do as he was trained immediately following the accident the leakage would have been eliminated.  The situation would have also been controlled quicker if the local fire and police officials would have allowed company personnel to get to the vehicle in a timely fashion, since they were more familiar with the equipment and how to cut-off the flow of product to the area that was damaged.  The company representative was allowed to eventually get to the vehicle about 2 hours after the incident and was allowed to instruct fire personnel how to cut-off the flow of materials.  If this had of been allowed immediately the situation would have been mitigated quickly and the evacuation of the local residence would not have been necessary.
column169: We have talked with all company drivers on how to react if they accidentally go of the road surface to try and prevent over-correction leading to loss of control of vehicles. Discussed with drivers the events of the accident and reminded them on importance of cutting off product flow at tank valve.     Would also recommend that local emergency response personnel be trained on the importance of allowing the company personnel to assist in controlling the situation since in most cases they are the subject matter expert both with the risks of the product and how the equipment operates.  This must be done immediately to help mitigate the situation. We understand the importance of the emergency responders in taking charge of the situation, but they must allow the company personnel to assist.  In this case something that could have been controlled in less than an hour took almost 7 hours.

The drum that released was being held in the 10 day waste holding area of the warehouse.  It was stored on the second level of the warehouse pushback racks. A total of four drums were on the pallet. As the pallet containing the drum was being taken down from the rack, the bolt ring on the drum got caught on the ring of another drum right behind it.  The two drums on the back end of the pallet fell onto the floor, an estimated distance of 12 feet.  One of the drums that fell did not leak. The open head cover of one drum broke off and the contents were released to the warehouse floor.  The liquid material was recovered by in-house employees and the waste material and damaged drum were put into an overpack drum.  No material was released to the environment.
column169: We will tape all waste drums stored on the elevated portion of the pushback racks.    Shipper will be contacted to determine if the waste material can be shipped in closed head drums.    Any future open head drums to be stored will have bolt turned to inside of pallet so it can't catch on top of another container.    Incident reviewed with warehouse employees during monthly safety meeting.

THE RESIN WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TOP OUTLET VALVE, AS THE RESIN WOULD BUILD UP IT WOULD FALL FROM THE VALVE AND DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CYLINDER.  THE CREW TIGHTENED THE TOP VALVE AND STOPPED THE RELEASE OF THE RESIN.  THE CYLINDER WAS ALLOWED TO SIT SEVERAL MINUTES BEFORE INSPECTED AGAIN AND NO VISUAL SIGNS OF LEAKAGE WERE DETECTED.  THE CREW DID NOT GENERATE ANY WASTE FROM THE INCIDENT.

column168: TRUCK WAS LOADED IN RICHMOND, CA AND DRIVEN TO VALLEJO, CA (25 MILES) IN ROUTE TO CLEAN OUT CAP (3" OPENING) ON THE TOP OF COMPARTMENT #1 CAME OFF. AS THE TRUCK TRAVELED UP OR DOWN AN INCLINE PRODUCT WOULD LEAK FROM THE OPENING, TRAVEL THROUGHT THE CATWALK TO THE UPPER DRAINS AND FINALLY TO THE HIGHWAY. BECAUSE THIS HAPPENED AT NIGHT THE DRIVER DID NOT SEE THE PRODUCT SPRAY BEHIND HIM NOR DID ANY MOTORIST BRING IT TO HIS ATTENTION (PROBABLY BECAUSE THE SPRAY WAS TOO LIGHT TO NOTICE).     WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY LOCATION HE NOTICED WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS THE TANK LEAKING. HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND THE CLEAN OUT CAP LYING IN THE CATWALK. BECAUSE A SMALL MOUNT OF PRODUCT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE STREET THE DRIVER CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THEY RESPONDED BUT DEEMED IT TO BE INSIGNIGICANT AND PULLED OFF THE SCENE.     SINCE ONLY AN ESTIMATED SPILL OF 5 GALLONS WAS AT THE SERVICE STATION SIGHT, THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT HAD SPRAYED OVER A 25 MILE JOURNEY. BOTH THAT SPILL AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT AT THE STATION HAD EVAPORATED BEFORE ANY CLEAN UP ACTION COULD BE INITIATED.
column169: A DETAILED ANALYSIS THAT ADDRESSES THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS VIA AN INFORMATION POSTER DISTRIBUTED TO ALL OUR TERMINAL AND DURING THE NEXT ROUND OF SAFETY MEETINGS BEGINNING IN FEBRUARY, 2006.

GATX 300846 WAS REPORTED LEAKING ABOUT ITS BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND NOZZLE WHILE CAR WAS AT CSX TRANSPORTATION, STANLEY YARD, WALBRIDGE OH.  LEAK WAS REPORTED AS ONE DROP EVERY 15 SECONDS.  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (ECESI), FINDLAY, OH WAS DISPATCHED BY CSX TRANSPORATION.  ECESI ADVISED THE PACKAING GLAND NUT FOR THE STUFFING BOX OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET ROD WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET ROD WAS TURNED THREE-QUARTERS OF A TURN (270 DEGRESS) AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE STUFFING BOX OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET ROD WAS MADE TOOL TIGHT.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED ONE-QUARTER OF A TURN (90 DEGRESS).  ECESI THUS SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  CAUSE CODE: 533 NARRI:5(5+3+1)X(2+0)=90

PLMX 4507. LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S SIBERT YARD IN MOBILE, AL.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONSED A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE STATE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SHIPPER, TRANSAMMONIA, INC, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE.  THE CONTRACTOR ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND NUT TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS SLOWED BUT COULD NOT BE STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE OVERFILLED AND WAS SHELL FULL.  TRANSAMMONIA ADVISED THAT THEY HAD A EMPTY CAR, PLMX 135011, IN SIBERT YARD.  THIS CAR WAS SPOTTED NEXT TO THE LEAKING CAR AND APPROXIMATELY 21 INCHED OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE PLMX 4507 INTO THE PLMX 135011.  TH "SPITTER" VALVE ON THE GAUGING DEVICE ON THE PLMX 4507 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DEFECTIVE.  A REPLACEMENT 1/4 INCH GATE VALVE WAS INSTALLED AND ALL PRODUCT LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED.  TRANSAMMOINIA OBTAIN AN FRA APPROVAL (FRA - 05110303) TO MOVE THE PLMX 4507 TO DETINATION.  CAUSE CODE:498 NARRI:5(5+9+0)X(2+0)=140

Driver stated that he was entering a curve at approx.50mph on Hwy 119 northbound when the truck began vibrating. It then tipped to the right, went over the hill and landed upside down. Fuel compartments #1 & #4 ruptured, resulting in a leakage of 3252 gallons of fuel.Response teams began gound clean-up asap.Gas company was notified and gas lines were shut off.A skimmer truck was placed at main point of fuel recovery on waterway. Also diapered and boomed spill.Remaining fuel was removed to another truck and tanker was resealed and ready for removal by 8:00 pm. Water samples taken by Williamson  water plant were found to be of good quality and water power was restored by 8:30 pm.Received permit to remove contaminated soil, hydroseed, and to restore to original slope per Highway Dept standards. Damaged guard rail to be replaced. KORC employees have continued to monitor the site and continue clean-up operations

column168: Driver completed transfer of product and started the final phase of unloading, breaking down the hoses. He was walking the hoses out with the assistance of the consignee. column168: Transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  According to calculations, there should have been plenty of room in the storage tank leaving more than a 10% outage.  By time the driver realized that the sight gauge was showing over 90% full and he shut down, the tank started to overflow.  Driver had 150 gallons still left in the cargo tank.  The spill went into a containment area and the customer told driver not to worry about cleanup.  They said they would handle it.
column169: Driver should have been monitoring sight gauge more closely even though there should have been plenty of room in the storage tank.

column168: Driver was delivering product in cargo tank to be transferred to customer storage tank.  Shipper rep for the consignee, looked at BOL and weights, got calibration chart for the storage tank and calculated how much to put in tank.  He told driver to stop the transfer of product when the gauge on the tank got to 99".  He then walked away.  Driver stopped the unload at 99" but product started to run out the overflow on the side of the tank.  Spill went into a containment area around the tank.  Driver still had 10 gallons left in trailer.  Customer is taking responsibility and said they would handle cleanup.
column169: The calibration chart for the customer's storage tank might not take into account a SIDE overflow vent.  It needs to be recalibrated.

column168: THIS IS THE DESCRIPTION OF AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A CARDINAL HEALTH VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING ON ROUTE 50 WHERE IT TOOK THE 495 NORTHBOUND EXIT.  WHILE TRAVELING ON THE EXIT RAMP THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO FLIP TWO TIMES.  THE TRUCK BED COVER WAS SEPARATED FROM THE VEHICLE RESULTING IN THE CARGO (AMMO CANS) BEING EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE.  ALL OF THE AMMO CANS HAD BROKEN OPEN FROM THE COLLISION.  THE VEHICLE WAS CARRYING SEVEN LQS RETURN PACKAGES FROM CUSTOMERS.  THERE WERE EIGHT UNIT DOSE LEAD PIGS AND SEVEN UNIT DOSE TUNGSTEN SHIELDS FOUND AT THE SCENE, AND THEY WERE ALL INTACT.  HOWEVER THERE WERE TWO BULK VIALS OF TC-99M DOSES THAT HAD COME OUT OF THEIR LEAD SHIELDING.  VIAL ONE ORIGINALLY CONTAINED 70 MCI OF TC-99M AT 10:00 AM ON NOVEMBER 27, 2005, AND VIAL ORIGINALLY CONTAINED 65 MCI OF TC99M AT 4:00 PM ON NOVEMBER 27, 2005.  THE APPROXIMATE AMOUNT OF ACTIVITY SPILLED WAS 600 UCI IN 10ML OF AQUEOUS SOLUTION.  SURVEYS WERE PERFORMED ON THE VEHICLE AND THE HIGHWAY SURFACE.  THE VEHICLE DID NOT HAVE ANY CONTAMINATION, BUT THERE WERE SMALL SPOTS OF CONTAMINATION OF THE HIGHWAY WHERE THE BULK TC-99M VIALS HAD BROKEN.  THESE SPOTS PRODUCED A SURVEY READING OF TWICE BACKGROUND.  THE AREAS WERE DECONTAMINATED BY CLEANING THE AREA WITH WINDEX AND WATER; REMOVING THE REMNANTS OF GLASS AND SAND; AND HAVING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HOSE THE AREA DOWN.
column169: DUE TO THE LARGE VOLUME OF DELIVERY VEHICLES UTILIZED BY CARDINAL HEALTH, ACCIDENTS OCCUR FROM TIME TO TIME.  CARDINAL HEALTH IS CONSTANTLY WORKING TO IMPROVE OUR DRIVER'S TRAINING AND SAFETY AWARENESS PROGRAMS.  IN THIS CASE THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WILL NO LONGER BE ALLOWED TO DRIVE FOR CARDINAL HEALTH, DUE TO THE SEVERITY OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE OTHER DRIVERS AT THIS LOCATION ARE ALSO BEING RETRAINED ON DRIVER SAFETY AND AWARENESS TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE.

column168: The trailer had been picked up one mile rom the accident site.  Driver was making a left turn when the trailer became disconnected from the tractor mid way through a turn, sliding off the road and overturning.  Some ot the tubes moved within the structure of the trailer.  There was not a release of product due to the accident itself.  As a safety precaution before uprighting, Linde Gas and local responders decided to vent the product from the trailer tubes in a controlled manner.  The trailer was successfully uprighted without further incident.  The roadway was open during the entire process.
column169: The driver involved was terminated.  It was determined that he had not used standard practices when connecting a tractor to a trailer which led up to the trailer coming loose in the turn.    Re-emphasis to all employees of proper connecting procedures is in process.    Considering the force of the impact, the trailer sustained minimal damage protected the integrity of the actual HM containment devices which were 3AA cylinders permanently affixed to the trailer.

column14: Old Pulaski Rd at Mitchell Rd
column168: Vehicle drifted off the right of the roadway, striking guard rail and bridge sidewall.  Vehicle then left road surface, falling from the bridge onto Old Pulaski Rd below, approximately a 25ft. fall.  Vehicle slid off road below overturning and catching fire due to rupture of the diesel fuel tank at initial point of impact.  Tractor burned completely causing fatal injuries to the driver.  Cargo tank had small puntcture in sidewall  close to heads due to impact with guardrail and was venting gaseous oxygen.    Cargo tank was lifted and placed on a flatbed trailer and taken approximaely 75 yardes to a local gravel pit where it remained under supervision to allow the remaining product to vent off prior to removal to a wrecking yard. Venting of the product to atmosphere took approximately 2 days to accomplish due to the piping at the rear fo the trailer being inoperable due to impact with road surface.
column169: Initial indications are that the accident may be fatigue related.  The driver was well within his hours of service limitations and and had only been on duty approximately 7 hours when the accident ocurred.  We have implemented a pilot test program with lane guidance and departure warning sytsems and have installed these and rollover/stability braking systems in test vehicles for evaluation purposes.    The cargo tank itself performed admirably as the impact to the road surface below did not actually cause the releas of product, impact with the guard rail caused the punture of the inner and outer shells of the cargo tank.  This is a cargo tank built in accordance with the exceptions allowed in 173.320.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the cargo building 23B at the JFK International Airport, free product was discovered leaking.  Approximately, fifty-five pounds of free product was released.  The Port Authority responded to the scene to contain the free product.  The Port Authority swept up the free product and placed it into 3, overpack drums.  The Port Authority placed plastic over the shipment.  H.M.H.T.T.C. of Elizabeth, New Jersey was contacted to perform the cleanup.  Upon investigation by H.M.H.T.T.C., it was determined that 12, 25 kilogram bags were leaking.  The release was due to the product leaking from the seams of the bag.  H.M.H.T.T.C. performed the cleanup using Level C protection.  H.M.H.T.T.C. placed the 12 leaking 25 kilogram bags into 2, 55 gallon recovery drums which was left at the facility to be returned to the shipper.  The remainder of the shipment was shrink-wrapped to a pallet and was also held pending shipper instructions.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  All Federal, State and local regulatory agencies were notified.
column169: Since the release was accidental and appears to be the result of faulty seams on the bags, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

A CALL WAS MADE TO THE CHEMICAL HELPLINE FOR ASSISTANCE.  WE DISCOVERED THE PLASTIC VALVE PORTION WAS SEPARATED FROM THE EXIT PIPING. THE REMAINING LIQUID FROM THE TOTE WERE PLACED IN 4 RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE CLEANUP WASTE AND OTHER CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS. RON STARTED THE PUMP AGAIN, SAW WATER SPRAYING, HE SHUT DOWN THE PUMP, GOT MINE PERSONAL TO RUN THE PUMP, WHILE HE STOOD ON TOP OF THE TRAILER TO LOCATE THE LEAK. ALL THE CYANIDE THAT LEAKED, ABOUT 1 GALLON ACCORDING TO RON WAS INSIDE OF THE CONTAINMENT PAD, WHICH WAS WASHED DOWN INTO THE SUMP AND PUMPED INTO MINE TANKAGE.  TRAILER WAS BLUE TAGGED UPON RETURN TO YARD AND IS WAITING TO BE REPAIRED AS WE SPEAK.

ON 11-23-05 WHILE OFFLOADING A TANKER TRUCK OF ACETONE, THE CHEMCRAFT OFFLOADER SWITCHED ON BALL VALVE ON THE IN-HOUSE STORAGE TANK CLOSED TO DIVERT THE FLOW OF ACETONE TO ANOTHER COMPARTMENT.  THE BALL VALVE DIDN'T GET CLOSED COMPLETELY AND ACETONE OVERFILLED A STORAGE TANK.  5 GALLONS OF ACETONE WAS SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE IN A AREA OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  AND WAS PROMPTLY CLEANED UP BY CHEMCRAFT PERSONNEL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AND ACETONE DIDN'T REACH SOIL OR WATER.  NO FOLLOW-UP NEEDED.  THIS DID NOT INVOLVE A PACKAGE FAILURE OF ANY KIND.  HUMAN ERROR CAUSED THIS SPILL.  THE POINT OF SPILL WAS AT A STATINOARY ON-SITE STORAGE TANK.

column168: BNSF TRAIN AND CREW OPERATING ON THE STILLWATER CENTRAL RAILROAD ON THE FORMER BNSF SOONER SUBDIVISON DERAILED ELEVEN RAILCARS ON SINGLE MAIN TRACK.  RAILCARS DERAILED INCLUDED TWO TANK CARS LADENED WITH MOLTEN SULFUR.  THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS A DETAIL FRACTURE BROKEN RAIL.  BOTH OF THE DERAILED MOLTEN SULFUR TANK CARS WERE ON THEIR SIDE AND ONE OF THESE (GATX 300393) LEAKED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY CLOSURE.  THE ESCAPING MOLTEN SULFUR SOLIDIFIED AND SEALED THE MANWAY CLOSURE WHICH ENDED THE ACTIVE PRODUCT RELEASE.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR EXCAVATED THE SOLIDIFIED SULFUR AND IMPACTED GROUND SOIL FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL IN A NEARBY LANDFILL.  GATX 300393 WAS DEEMED DESTROYED AND EARMARKED FOR FUTURE CLEANING AND DISMANTLING.  THE LOCAL P.D. INITIATED AN EVACUATION OF NEARBY RESIDENCES AND THE EXACT NUMBER OF PEOPLE IMPACTED BY THIS EVACUATION IS UNKNOWN.  THE EVACUATION LASTED FOR APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS.  AN OKLAHOMA CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE UNIT ALSO RESPONDED TO THIS INCIDENT.

No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: OUTBOUND DRIVER AT THE BNSF INTERMODAL FACILITY REPORTED CONTAINER HDMU 634677 LEAKING AN UNKNOWN GREEN LIQUID SUBSTANCE OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THIS CONTAINER.  HDMU 634677 WAS TAKEN TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY CONTAINMENT AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECTING THE INTERIOR OF HDMU 634677 REPORTED THAT THE INTERIOR BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS INSUFFICIENT TO RESTRAIN THE LADING.  THE TOP TIER OF 55 GALLON STEEL CLOSED HEAD DRUMS LOADED WITH A MAGNAFLUX PRODUCT LABELED ZYGLO ZL67 (A CLASS 9 SHIPPED MATERIAL) HAD SHIFTED.  ONE SHIFTED DRUM CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE CONTAINER'S SIDEWALL WHICH RESULTED IN DRUM SIDEWALL DENTS AND STRESS FRACTURES ALONG THE DRUM'S TOP ROLLING HOOP.  THIS LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK OR RECOVERY DRUM.  THE INTERIOR AND EXTERIOR OF HDMU 634677 WAS CLEANED OF ALL SPILLAGE.  ALL LADING, INCLUDING THE RECOVERY DRUM, WAS RELOADED BACK INTO THE CLEANED CONTAINER, PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION (EXPORT VIA OCEAN VESSEL.)
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER PROPERLY BLOCKS AND BRACES INTERMODAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS TO FULLY RESTRAIN LADING DURING NORMAL TRANSPORTATION MOVEMENTS.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: INTERMODAL CONTAINER HUNU 663775 ON RAIL FROM SEATTLE TO CHICAGO WAS BEING DRAYED OVER THE ROAD FOR INTERCHANGE TO THE NS RR IN CHICAGO.  THE NS RR REJECTED INTERCHANGE OF HUNU 663775 AT THEIR IN-GATE DUE TO THE CONTAINER DRIPPING AN UNKNOWN LIQUID SUBSTANCE.  HUNU 663775 RETURNED TO THE BNSF CICERO INTERMODAL FACILITY AND WAS PLACED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA FOR INVESTIGATION INTO THE LEAK SOURCE.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS TESTED LEAK DRIPS AND FOUND THEM TO BE ACIDIC.  INSIDE HUNU 663775 FIVE LARGE INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES (APPROX. 2000 LBS EACH) WHERE INDIVIDUALLY BANDED ON WOODEN PALLETS.  NO OTHER BLOCKING AND BRACING FOR THESE BATTERIES WERE EVIDENT.  TWO OF THE BATTERIES HAD SHIFTED ON THEIR PALLETS BREAKING THE THIN BANDING.  ONE BATTERY NEAR THE DOORWAY TIPPED OVER SPILLING THE BATTERY ACID WITHIN.  RESPONDERS NEUTRALIZED AND WIPED SPILLAGE IN THE INTERIOR AND ON THE EXTERIOR OF HUNU 663775.  BATTERIES WERE REBANDED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED INSIDE HUNU 663775 FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER PROPERLY BLOCKS AND BRACES INTERMODAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS TO FULLY RESTRAIN LADING DURING NORMAL TRANSPORTATION MOVEMENTS.

column168: F.E. WARREN ORDERED 1085 GALLONS OF GASOHOL TO BE PUT IN 1500 GAL. VAULTED TANK.  TANK HAS 3" ADAPTER FITTING AND AFTER PUTTING IT ON AND SECURING LINE-STARTED TO PUMP FUEL INTO TANK-AT 360 GALLON MARK CHECK CONNECTIONS AND FOUND FUEL IN ADAPTER CONTANINMENT AT WHICH TIME HURRIED TO STOP PUMP (385 GAL. MARK).  FUEL STARTED COMING OUT VENT RELEASE AT ADAPTER CONTAINMNET AND DUE TO CONFUESION ON WHY THIS WAS HAPPENING DRIVER TOOK ADAPTER FITTING OFF WHICH RESULTED IN GASOHOL VENTING FROM FITTING OPENING-UPON THIS I FIGURED THE PRESSURE VENTS (BOTH-NORMAL AND EMERGENCY) MALFUNCTIONED AND TANK WAS PRESSURED UP OVER VENT REQUIREMENTS.  WHEN GASOHOL FLOW SUBSIDED DRIVER OPENED EMERGENCY VENT AND GOT PRESSURE OFF TANK RESULTING IN GASOHOL NOT FLOWING.  APROX. 80 GALS. WERE EST. AT SPILL.
column169: OVERHEAD VENTS AT THE TOP VENT RISERS SHOULD BE REPLACED-THERE ARE PLASITC ON THE GASOHOL TANKS AND METAL ONTHE DIESEL-THESE SHOULD BE CHECKED AND REPLACED PERIODICALLY-BUGS, DIRT AND OTHER DEBRIS GET IN THEM AND KEEP THEM FROM WORKING CORRECTLY.  SPILL PREVENTION ALSO CAN BE LESSENED IF EMERGENCY VENT IS POPPED OPEN DURING FILLING-THIS WOULD NOT BE A CLOSED SYSTEM BUT NO SPILL WOULD OCCUR.

column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: Driver was making a delivery at 12 Gary Street. He set his preset for 100 gallons and connected his scully to the tank and made the delivery. Once the preset shut off, he left scully attached and went and checked his meter. It showed 97 gallons had been delivered. He then returned to the tank and pumped three more gallons in for a total of 100 gallons. With the scully still attached to the tank, he went to front door of the trailer and collected. a check for the delivery. He then proceeded directly to the truck cab and drove four places down the road to make his next delivery. The hose continued to reel out, pulling the horizontal tank off its blocks and bending lwo legs underneath. No leakage occurred at the tank. The hose finally separated from the hose reel causing kerosene from the hose to spill on the street. It is estimated that 20 gallons was lost from the hose. Upon arrival at 20 Gary Street, driver left truck and went to residence to collect $280.13 cash prior to making the delivery. He then walked di:rectly to the meter at the rear of the truck with cash in hand and a ticket for the customer. He placed ticket in meter and charged his line. He dumped 12.5 gallons over himself and onto the ground before he was able to shut the pump down. Based on interviews with the driver by District Manager and Branch Manager, the driver denies ever hearing the hose break away or noticing that the hose was missing. Driver immediately reported spill to Branch Manager via cellphone and requested all available assistance for a major spill.
column169: How could Spill/Leak have been prevented: This spill was the result of driver inattention and failure to follow standard procedures. Under no circumstances should a driver walk away from a scully attached to the fill. As soon as the preset shut off, he should have disconnected and returned the scully to the truck. If the requested amount was not delivered than he could return to the tank and pump the additional amount or the billing could be adjusted if the check was not already written. If there was a consistent underpump with the preset, he could have set it for 103 gallons. A three gallon.

ON SATURDAY NOVEMBER 12, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM, FRANK TERRELL WAS APPLYING NH3 FRANK WAS USING AGROLSKY, ADEBANDURAS, TOOL BAR AND NH3 NURSE TANK # AK 25.  THE HITCH PIN ON THE WAGON WASHED OUT.  THE PIONEER SAFETY BREAKAWAY DID NOT FUNCTION IMMEDIATELY.  AS A RESULT THE BREAKING THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS SCREWED INTO BROKE.  THIS RESULTED IN THE AIRBORNE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2000 # OF NH3.  THE RELEASE WAS 100% AIRBORNE.  LUCKILY FRANK WAS DRIVING SOUTH AT THE TIME.  THERE WAS A SSW WIND OF BETWEEN 15-20 MPH.  NOBODY WAS INJURED AND NOBODY HAD TO BE EVACUATED.  IDEU# 200511118.  NRC# 779353.  THE NH3 TANK WAS A 1000 GAL TANK.  THE EVENT HAPPENED ON THE SOUTH WEST CORNER OF 1400 S 50 W.  KENTLAND WAS THE CLOSEST TOWN.  KENTLAND IS SOUTH WEST OF THE INCIDENT.  THE EVENT HAPPENED IN NEWTON COUNTY SECTION 14.  REPORTING FOR CUSTOMER.  FRANK TERRELL 219-474-6845 1:30-145 TONY CALLED BILL LIESTER.   BILL LIESTER LEFT MESSAGE WITH STEVE SOLOMAN 1:50.  BILL LIESTER CALLED MIKE FETUS 1:55.  BILL LIESTER DROVE FROM RENSSELAER TO CALL IDEM & NRC.  IDEM CALLED HARLEY 2:30 NRC CALLED 2:42 REPORT #779353 JEFF CREWS RICK HACKELL W/IDEM CALLED 2:50 SPILL # 200511118  JOHN W/ LEPC CALLED 3:15 TOLD HIM WHAT HAPPENED.  HE WANTED TO CHECK W/SUPERVISOR & SEE IF THEY NEEDED ANY FURTHER INFO.

EMPLOYEE CHRIS REARDON WAS TRAVELING DOWN THE DOCK WITH A PALLET OF LOOSE BOXES FROM THE SHIPPER, THERMO ELECTRON, WHEN ONE OF THE BOXES FELL OFF OF THE PALLET ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR AND SPLIT OPEN. ABOUT 1 PINT OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID SPILLED OUT. THE SINGLE BOX WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND THE MIXTURE OF THE SPEEDY DRY AND THE SPILLED CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS PLACED INTO A DIFFERENT RECOVERY DRUM- BOTH WERE SEALED AND LABELED. THE HOLE IN THE INNER METAL BOX WAS NOT SEEN AS THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE CORRUGATED OUTSIDE BOX. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED QUICKLY AND THE CLEAN UP WAS CONDUCTED IN-HOUSE. THE EVENT LASTED ABOUT 20 MINUTES.
column169: WE ARE STILL INTERVIEWING EMPLOYEES THAT WERE THERE AT THE TIME TO INSURE THAT WE HAVE ALL OF THE INFORMATIN THAT CAN BE GAINED, BUT THE EMPLOYEE WILL BE FORKLIFT RETRAINED AND INSTRUCTED TO STRETCH-WRAP ANY AND ALL LOOSE BOXES OF HAZMAT FREIGHT BEFORE IT TRAVELS DOWN THE DOCK ON A FORKLIFT.

column168: WHILE LOADING DOCK FREIGHT DSR SHERMAN FRAZIER SMELLED THE SPILL AND CLEANED IT UP. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED FROM ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT THAT WAS HANGING OFF THE SKID. column169: IN THE FUTURE WE MUST ALL BE MORE AWARE OF OUR ENVIRONMENT AND TAKE CARE TO ELIMINATE ANY FUTURE SPILLS.

column169: LOI.

column168: DAVID MCBRIDE, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THERE IS A STRONG ODOR IN THE PROXIMITY OF TANK CAR CITX 34439, LOCATED IN THE RAIL YARD IN LIVONIA, LA.  MR. MCBRIDE STATED NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS WERE COMPLETED.  ROBINSON ADVISED HE HAD INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THE CAUSE WAS A LOOSE PACKING NUT ON THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  MR. ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE NUT, WHICH SECURED THE RELEASE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Gauging Device
column168: CHAD CRABTREE, YARDMASTER, REPORTED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE IN TO THE LIVONIA YARD, LIVONIA, LA.  MR. CRABTREE ADVISED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF MATERIAL HAD DRIPPED FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 300696.  MR. CRABTREE STATED THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  NECESSARY STATE, FEDERAL, AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 05:49 PM, ROBINSON ADVISED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS AN IMPROPERLY INSTALLED PLUG FOR THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  MR. ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND INSTALLED THE PLUG, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  ROBINSON REPORTED THE TANK CAR WAS SECURE AND SPILLED PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATING.
column169: SHIPPER TO REVIEW TANK CAR LOADING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.

LIMITED QUANTITY PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AND BROKE THE GLASS INNER BOTTLE.  PACKAGE WAS REJECTED DUE TO IMPROPER DOCUMENTATION AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

BRUCE PENNER'S HIRE HAND (JORDAN THIESSEN) HAD JUST HOOKED ONTO A FULL JUMBO TANK (3 TON) OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND OPENED ALL THE VALVES. THE TANK HITCH ON THE IMPLEMENT IS AN ADJUSTABLE HITCH DESIGNED TO PULL OUT AND MANEUVER TO EASE HOOKING UP TANKS. THE HITCH WAS PULLED COMPLETELY OUT TO HOOK UP TO THIS TANK, SO THE TRACTOR WOULD HAVE TO BE BACKED INTO THE TANK, OR PULLED FORWARDS AND STOPPED QUICKLY TO MOVE THE ADJUSTABLE HITCH INTO TOWING POSITION. JORDAN SAID THAT HE NOTICED THAT THE HOSE HAD A SMALL LOOP IN IT WHEN HE HOOKED IT UP TO THE IMPLEMENT COUPLER, BUT HE THOUGHT NOTHING OF IT BECAUSE IT WAS NEARLY TOUCHING THE GROUND NOT COILED. HE PULLED FORWARD AND QUICKLY STOPPED TO LOCK IN THE QUICK HITCH AND HE HEARD A SHARP POP AND THEN QUICKLY REALIZED THAT IT WAS THE HOSE RUPTURING. AT THIS TIME, JORDAN ATTEMPTED TO GET THE TRACTOR AND IMPLEMENT INTO A POSITION THAT WAS UPWIND. HE BEGAN MOVING TOWARDS THE SOUTH, SOUTHWEST BUT COULD NOT FIND A POSITION TO GET AWAY FROM THE QUICKLY ERUPTING CLOUD. AT THAT TIME, HE CALLED BRUCE ON THE RADION AND TOLD HIM WHAT HAD HAPPENED. BRUCE WAS JUST ACROSS THE SECTION, WENT TO A NEIGHBORING HOUSE AND CALLED 911. ONCE JORDAN RAN OUT OF ROOM TO MANEUVER IN THE FAR SW CORNER, (THE MIDDLE OF THE SECTION) HE EVACUATED FROM THE TRACTOR CAB AND RAN BACK TO THE NORTH NORTHEAST TOWARDS BUTLER ROAD. JORDAN COMMENTED THAT AFTER HE WAS OUT OF THE CAB, THE WIND WAS VERY LIGHT, AND IF ANY AT ALL, IT WAS OUT OF THE NORTHWEST. THE SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT BEGAN TO ARRIVE SHORTLY AFTER 6:00PM. UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT, THE OFFICIALS TOLD JORDAN TO REMAIN AT A SAFE DISTANCE.  AT 6:30, LELAND RECEIVED A CALL AT HOME FROM THE BUTLER COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT CONCERNING A LEAKING ANHYDROUS TANK. THEY ASKED HIM TO GO TO 40TH AND BUTLER ROAD. WHEN HE GOT THERE, THE BENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD THE WHOLE SECTION BLOCKED. HE PROCEEDED TO THE STATE TROOPER THAT WAS BLOCKING OFF BUTLER ROAD AND TOLD HIM WHO HE WAS AND THE TROOPER TOLD HIM TO PROCEED DOWN THE DITCH AND FIND THE BENTON FIRE CHIEF. WHEN LELAND GOT TO THE SCENE, NO ONE HAD YET APPROACHED THE TANK TO SEE WHAT ACTION TO TAKE. FIRE CHIEF REX STEPHENS ASKED LELAND IF HE WOULD ASSIST HIM AND GO TO THE TANK AND SEE IF THEY COULD SHUT IT OFF. WHEN THEY GOT WITHIN 40 FEET OF THE TANK, IT BECAME OBVIOUS THAT THEY WERE NOT GOING TO BE ABLE TO APPROACH THE TANK TO TURN OFF THE VALVE. AT THAT TIME, THEY MOVED AWAY TO A SAFER POSITION AND REASSESSED THE SITUATION. UPON REASSESSMENT, THE TANK WAS BEGINNING TO SLOW DOWN IN LIQUID RELEASE SO CHIEF STEPHENS CALLED IN A FIRE TRUCK TO LAY DOWN A WATER MIST, HE SUITED INTO SCBA GEAR AND APPROACHED THE TANK AND SHUT OFF THE VALVE. BY THE TIME THE VALVE HAD BEEN CLOSED, LITTLE OR NO LIQUID WAS ESCAPING, MOSTLY VAPOR WAS BEING RELEASED. THE AREA WAS ALLOWED TO AIR FOR SOME TIME AND THEN BRUCE PENNER WAS ALLOWED TO RETURN TO HIS ANHYDROUS APPLICATION.  EXPOSURE OCCURRED TO A PREGNANT WOMAN LIVING IN THE AREA WHEN SHE CAME WITHIN

WHILE WALKING THROUGH THE AREA, TWO PASSERS-BY DETECTED A STRONG ODOR OF GAS IN AND AROUND TANK CARS BEING STORED AT WANAMAKER YARD, ESSINGTON, PA.  6:30 PM: CR RISK MANAGEMENT A. RICHTER WAS CONTACTED AND ENROUTE TO INVESTIGATE.  MR. RICHTER ALSO CONTACTED REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOR ASSISTANCE.  CUSTOMER OF CARS BEING STORED, CONOCO PHILLPS, TRAINER, PA, ALSO CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  7:30 PM: ESSINGTON, PA FIRE DEPARTMENT, ON SCENE SINCE THE INITIAL NOTIFCATION, ADVISED THEY WERE DEPARTING THE AREA AND GAVE MR. RICHTER A CELL NUMBER SHOULD THEY BE REQUIRED BACK AT THE SCENE.  REACT REPRESENTATIVE FOUND TANK CAR PLMX 3844, LOAD LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS, 2.1, UN 1075, DOT 112J400W, WITH FROST ON "B" END LIQUID VALVE, INDICATING A LIQUID LEAK.  WHEN CAR WAS IDENTIFIED, CR OPERATIONS AND CUSTOMER SERVICE FOUND CAR WAS SHIPPED BY NGL SUPPLY, MARYSVILLE, MI.  CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER FOUND THE CAR'S CONTENTS TO BE BUTANE (INTERNAL PRESSURE GAUGED AT TIME OF INCIDENT INDICATED 48 P.S.I.)  VALVE NOTED NOT TOTALLY CLOSED, AND CLOSURE PLUG FOR SAID VALVE APPLIED TO VALVE'S FACEPLATE BY MERELY 1-2 THREADS.  VALVE CLOSED, PLUG MADE TOOL TIGHT AND LEAK SECURED.  TWO REPRESENTATIVES FROM CONOCO PHILLIPS, TRAINER, PA, WERE ALSO ON SCENE.  DURING ADDITIONAL EXAMINATION OF ALL OTHER VALVES INSIDE HOUSING PRIOR TO DECLARING THE CAR SECURE FOR TRANSPORTATION, THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS ALSO NOTED TO NOT BE TOTALLY CLOSED.  WHEN THE VALVE'S OPERATING HANDWHEEL WAS MADE SECURE, A WRENCH WAS APPLIED TO THE CLOSURE PLUG.  UPON TIGHTENING THE PLUG, THE VALVE BEGAN TO LEAK LIQUID.  WHEN SAFE TO DO SO, THE CLOSURE PLUG WAS REMOVED, REMAINING LIQUID INSIDE THE VALVE'S CHAMBER ALLOWED TO DISIPATE, AND THE THREADED PLUG, WITH TEFLON TAPE NOW APPLIED TO THE THREADS, WAS APPLIED AND MADE TOOL TIGHT.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  CAR OKAYED FOR MOVEMENT TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE, CONOCO PHILLIPS, TRAINER, PA REFINERY, FOR UNLOADING, AND INSPECTION/REPAIR/REPLACEMENT OF NOTED

column168: SAFEWAY'S DRIVER MR. OSCAR WALLEY DIED IN THIS ACCIDENT.  MR. WALLEY PICKED UP HIS TRAILER THAT WAS PRELOADED AT AKZO NOBEL, FUNCTIONAL CHEMICALS, AND LLC 13440 HWY 43 NORTH, AXIS, ALABAMA EARLY THE MORNING OF 11/28/05.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 46,340 LBS OF 98% LIQUID SULFURIC ACID.  MR. WALLEY WAS TRAVELING IN ROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION G.E.O. SPECIALTIES COMPANY, DEMOPOLIS, AL.  IN ROUTE, HE RAN OFF OF THE ROAD INTO A WOODED AREA LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES NORTH OF GROVE HILL, ALABAMA.  HE WAS DRIVING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 43, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 AM, WHEN HE LEFT THE HIGHWAY AT AN UNKONWN RATE OF SPEED, AND ACCORDING TO A WITNESS DID NOT CORRECT HIS PATH, NOR SEEM TO SLOW DOWN.  HE IMPACTED A TREE, AND THE CAB OF THE TRACTOR BURST INTO FLAMES.  THE TRAILER THAT HE WAS PULLING WAS LOADED WITH 46340 LBS OF 98% LIQUID SULFURIC ACID.  UPON IMPACT, THE TRAILER CARRIED OVER THE TRACTOR, AND LEAKED ALMOST ALL OF THE CONTENTS INTO THE TRACTOR AND ON TO THE GROUND.  THERE WERE ONLY LIMITED REMAINS.  AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, THEY WERE COLLECTED AND TRANSFERRED TO THE MOBILE CORONERS OFFICE.  THE TRAILER RIPPED AND LEAKED OUT AT THE FRONT BOTTOM RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE GASH WAS APPROXIMATELY SIX INCHES IN LENGTH, AND APPROXIMATELY AN INCH WIDE.  THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 0530 HOURS AND STOPPED LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HRS.  IT WAS CAUSED BY THE IMPACT, WHICH IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN IN EXCESS OF 50 MPH.  THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THAT LOCATION ONLY.  THE ACCIDENT SITE WAS CLEANED AND REMEDIATION COMPLETED BY A CONTRACTOR, COMPLETE ENVIRONMENTAL AND REMEDIATION CO, LLC, OUT OF BAY MINETTE, AL.  OUR INSURER, ZURICH OF NORTH AMERICAN SENT A SITE COORDINATOR TO THE ACCIDENT, WHO WORKED WITH THE PARTIES ON THE SCENE TO MINIMIZE THE DAMAGE, AND ENSURE THAT THE ACTIVITIES WERE TO STANDARD.  OUR TERMINAL MANAGER, MR. RANDY MINCHEW, AND OUR TERMINAL MECHANIC ALSO WENT TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  MR. MINCHEW MAINTAINED SAFEWAY'S PRESENCE TO CONTINUE TO ENSURE ADEQUATE WORK EFFORTS AND PROGRESS WITH THE CLEAN UP DURING THE SUBSEQUENT DAYS THE REMEDIATION WAS BEING ACCOMPLISHED.  TROOPER DARREL LINDER, WITH THE ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY / TRAFFIC HOMICIDE INVESTIGATION DEPT. AND AN ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTIONIST WERE ON HAND AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  MR. J. BERT SMITH, OUT OF THE MOBILE FIELD OFFICE FOR ADEM WAS ALSO PRESENT AT THE SCENE.  MR. ROY WAITE, OF THE CLARK COUNTY EMA WAS A KEY COORDINATOR AND COMMUNICATED WITH ME THROUGHOUT THE FIRST TWO DAYS.)  OTHER FIRST RESPONDERS SUCH AS THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND AMBULANCE PERSONNEL WERE PRESENT.  AFTER DAY ONE, COMPLETE ENVIRONMENTAL REMAINED ON THE SCENE DURING DAYLIGHT, AND BROUGHT THE AREA TO A SATISFACTORY REMEDIATION.

JOHN HART, YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 204407 WAS LEAKING AN UNDISCLOSED AMOUNT OF ETHANOL FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MARK, HILLOGRAPH, IOWA ETHANOL, (SHIPPER), ADVISED A REPRESENTATIVE WOULD RESPOND TO SECURE THE TANKCAR AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM.

column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED A LEAKIGN CONTAINER AT OUTBOUND GATE AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA.  MR. SANCHEZ ADVISED A YELLOW LIQUID WAS DRIPPING FROM CONTAINER KNLU 336340, PLACARDED FLAMMABLE.  MR. SANCHEZ ADVISED THE DRIPPING LIQUID WAS PUDDLING ON THE GROUND.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 12:49PM, MANAGER COOPER ADVISED ONE PINT OF THE LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED, DRIPPING FROM THE CENTER AREA OF THE CONTAINER FLOORING.  MANAGER COOPER ADVISED THE LEAK HAD BEEN CONTAINED.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION, WHICH SHOWED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED.  AT 02:48PM, THE SHIPPER (CHEVRON) HAD BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK, AND WOULD CONTACT THEIR DISTRIBUTOR.  AFTER SEVERAL DAYS OF NO CONTACT FROM THE DISTRIBUTOR, CHEVRON WAS RECONTACTED AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE LADING REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  DEVELOPED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM FROM THE FLOOR TIER, AGAINST THE MIDSHIP LEFT SIDE WALL, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN REPAIRED IN THE LOCATION OF THE DRUM, AND THE SMALL REPAIR SECTIONS OF THE FLOORING FLEXED UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUMS.  THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN PEELED BACK, WHICH IS A NORMAL INDICATION OF THE CHIME STRIKING AN ELEVATED FLOOR SCREW DURING LOADING.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT SEVERAL OF THE FLOOR SCREWS USED IN THE FLOOR REPAIR WERE SLIGHTLY ELEVATED, WHICH WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE CHIME CONDITION.  THE DRUM CHIME WAS PATCHED, AND THEN PLACED IN TO A SALVAGE DRUM TO SECURE THE PRODUCT.  THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE DISTRIBUTOR PER CHEVRON'S REQUEST.  SINCE THE FLOORING IN THE EXISTING CONTAINER WAS NOT TO STANDARD, ANOTHER CONTAINER WAS REQUESTED, WHICH WAS DELIVERED ON 11/17/05.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO CONTAINER GLDU 31674 FOR THE CONTINUED EXPORT MOVEMENT.

column168: 11-22-05 11:30am Midwest Gacy Wagner received a telephone call from Rick Hunt Crawford Co. to dispatch spill response personnel and equipment to the above spill site address to remediate an acid release. Approximately 700 gallons of Hi Temp Acid — 1000 were released during off loading operations. The spill migrated into the underground storm water drain line that emptied into an on site retention pond. Midwest Claude Reece and Ty 1-larweger, Cort Acres Facility Manager invcstigattxl the spill site prior to commencing remedial operations. An earthen dam was built in the ditch prior to it discharging into an on site retention pond. Midwest pcrsonncl pumped approximately 750 gallons of concentrated acid and water (into totes) from the ditch. Mike Sutton of the Indiana Department of Environmental Management (IDEM) was on site prior to Midwest arrival. David Gray of I3ork Transport arrived on site. Midwest Gary Wagner arranged for subcontractor support on I 1-23-05. 6:00pm Midwest personnel secured the area and departed.  11-23-05 7:30am Midwest personnel on site. Prior to flushing the storm drain with water a pit was dug in the ditch to collect any residual acid trapped in the storm drain. A vacuum truck was used to pump acid arid water from the storm drain during water flushing operations. This operation continued until the discharged water had a ph of 7. Midwest personnel hand dug and placed contaminated soil and gravel In 7-55-gallon di-urns in the truck off-loading area where the spill occurred. This area was purged With water. The purged water was collected and placed in 5-55 gatton poly drums. Contaminated soil in the ditch area was excavated, placed on poly sheeting within a dyke area. Poly sheeting was used to cover the contaminated soil. This material will be placed in a roll otTcontaincr to be düposed of at a later date. 3:1 5pm Midwest personnel secured the area and departed.  11-25-05 8:30am Midwest personnel on site, 9:30am roll olcontainer and subcontractor skid loader arrived on Site. 10:00am completed the loading of the roll off box. The roil off box will be transported to our Midwest Charlestown, [N facility for treatment and disposal. Used skid loader to contour the soil in the cffectcd areas. Placed grass seed and straw in the effected areas. Used ph paper to check the storm water ditch area. Ph paper tested at 7 or neutral. 12:45pm personnel secured the area and departed.  1 1-30-05 9:55am Midwest Wagner delivered the manifest to the roll off driver at the Cort Acres site, The driver signed the manifest and departed the site.  12-12-05 loaded and transported all drumnied material to our Midwest Charlestown, TN facility for treatment and disposal.  There is no additional work to be done at this time.

column168: CDG Project ft 090580500   CDG Engineers & Associates (COG) was contacted at approximately 8:30 AM by the management of Home Oil Company, located in Cowarts Alabama, and advised of an accident involving one of their transport vehicles with diesel fuel being the product on board. Following discussions with Mr. Robert Shepard of CDG and Rome Oil Company, CDG was contracted to manage the environmental aspects, including the contaminated soil removal and disposal, at the accident site.   COG responded to the accident site equipped with an assortment of absorbent materials to assist in the containment of any free product.   Upon arrival at the site the Home Oil Company transport vehicle had been off loaded of all remaining product. The damaged vehicle had been up righted and removed from the accident site.   Upon arrival COG personnel met with Mr. Jerry Cheatwood with the Alabama Department of Environmental Management (ADEM) and conducted a full evaluation of the accident / release site. It was reported to COG by Mr. Cheatwood that the accident resulted in a release of approximately 300-350 gallons of diesel fuel. COG was advised the Alabama Department of Trunsportation (ALDOT) road crews had been on site and utilized sand spread within the area to assist in absorbing free product. CDG and AIJEM determined that an excavation area approximately 40’ x 12’ would be needed to remove the contaminated soil from the site. It was also determined that the right-of-way along Hwy 110 contained water mains and fiber optic cables that ran the complete length of the needed excavation area. Service personnel were notified of this situation and responded to the site to assist with locating all utilities in the identified excavation area prior to the soil removal process.   CDG contracted with McDonald Construction of Union Springs Alabama to assist with the contaminated soil removal and transport for disposal. Mr. Jimmy McDonald responded with crews arriving on site at approximately 12:30 PM. McDonald Construction assisted COG with one John Deere 135C excavator and three 20 cubic yard dump trucks to remove the diesel fuel contaminated soils.   Two loads, approximately 42 cubic yards, of contaminated soil were excavated from the spill area. This contaminated soil was transported by McDonald Construction to Tallassee Waste Disposal, Inc. (Sunflower Landfill Permit 462-i 1R) for disposal.   Prior to transportation and disposal of the contaminated soil, emergency approval from ADEM had been obtained by COG for disposal. During the transportation process each vehicle was given a completed Manifest for Non-Hazardous Special Waste before leaving the spill site. Copies of the manifest are included in this report.  Following the excavation of the contaminated soil from the site, CDG obtained confirmation PAR samples from within the excavation.
